## What are Python variables?
Python variables are like boxes, like everything else in Python, they are objects that are used to store data values for computation. 
Unlike many other programming languages, variables are not declared. They are simply created once
a value has been assigned to them. The variable data types do not have to be declared, instead Python will infer the data type once a value has been assigned. A variable is only a name given to a memory location for later use.

## Example of assigning values to variables
# Assigning a string value to a variable
name = "Jack"
# Assigning an integer value to a variable
age = 30
# Assigning a float value to a variable
height = 1.75
# Assigning a boolean value to a variable
is_student = True
# Assigning a list value to a variable
fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
# Assigning a dictionary value to a variable
person = {"name": "Alice", "age": 25, "city": "NewYork"}
# Assigning a tuple value to a variable
coordinates = (10.0, 20.0)
# Assigning a set value to a variable
unique_numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
# Assigning a None value to a variable
result = None
# Assigning a complex number value to a variable
complex_number = 2 + 3j
# Assigning a byte value to a variable
byte_data = b"Hello, World!"  

